# Test Analysis: ui_text_box (ui_text_box.h.spec.md)

## Summary
All 3 test cases fail. Each failure is the same root cause: after calling one
of the three initialization functions, `the_kind_of_ui_element__this_is` is
set to `5` instead of the expected `UI_Element_Kind__Text_Box` (value `6`).

## Failures

### Failure 1 — test at line 21
- Assertion: `ui_element.the_kind_of_ui_element__this_is == UI_Element_Kind__Text_Box`
- Got: `5`, Expected: `6`
- Likely init function under test: `initialize_ui_element_as__text_box_with__const_c_str`

### Failure 2 — test at line 43
- Assertion: `ui_element.the_kind_of_ui_element__this_is == UI_Element_Kind__Text_Box`
- Got: `5`, Expected: `6`
- Likely init function under test: `initialize_ui_element_as__text_box_with__pM_c_str`

### Failure 3 — test at line 63
- Assertion: `ui_element.the_kind_of_ui_element__this_is == UI_Element_Kind__Text_Box`
- Got: `5`, Expected: `6`
- Likely init function under test: `initialize_ui_element_as__text_box_with__buffer_size`

## Root Cause Analysis

All three initialization functions in `ui_text_box.c` delegate to their
corresponding `initialize_ui_element_as__text_with__*` functions and then call
`initialize_ui_text_box__default_handlers`. Neither step sets
`the_kind_of_ui_element__this_is` to `UI_Element_Kind__Text_Box`.

The delegated `initialize_ui_element_as__text_with__*` functions set the kind
to `UI_Element_Kind__Text` (value `5`). The text box initializers never
override this field to `UI_Element_Kind__Text_Box` (value `6`).

## Required Fix

In each of the three initialization functions in `ui_text_box.c`, after
delegating to the corresponding text initializer and after calling
`initialize_ui_text_box__default_handlers`, explicitly set:

    p_ui_text_box->the_kind_of_ui_element__this_is =
        UI_Element_Kind__Text_Box;

This must be done in all three functions:
- `initialize_ui_element_as__text_box_with__const_c_str`
- `initialize_ui_element_as__text_box_with__pM_c_str`
- `initialize_ui_element_as__text_box_with__buffer_size`

## Additional Bug Noted (not tested, but present in source)

In `m_ui_element__typed_handler__text_box__alphanumeric`, the range checks use
exclusive comparisons (`>` and `<`) instead of inclusive (`>=` and `<=`),
which incorrectly excludes the boundary characters `'0'`, `'9'`, `'a'`, `'z'`,
`'A'`, and `'Z'` from valid input. These should be changed to `>=` and `<=`.
